{{Infobox court case |name = Larbi-Odam v MEC for Education (North-West Province) |italic title = no |court = [[Constitutional Court of South Africa]] |image = |imagesize = |imagelink = |imagealt = |caption = |full name = Larbi-Odam and Others v the Member of the Executive Council for Education (North-West Province) and Another |date decided = {{Start date|1997|11|26|df=y}} |citations = {{cite SAFLII|court=ZACC|year=1997|num=16|parallelcite=1997 (12) BCLR 1655, 1998 (1) SA 745}} |transcripts = |judges = [[Arthur Chaskalson|Chaskalson]] [[President of the Constitutional Court of South Africa|P]], [[Pius Langa|Langa]] [[Deputy President of the Constitutional Court of South Africa|DP]], [[Lourens Ackermann|Ackermann]], [[John Didcott|Didcott]], [[Richard Goldstone|Goldstone]], [[Johann Kriegler|Kriegler]], [[Tholie Madala|Madala]], [[Yvonne Mokgoro|Mokgoro]], [[Kate O'Regan|O'Regan]] & [[Albie Sachs|Sachs]] JJ |number of judges = 10 |decision by = Mokgoro |prior actions = |appealed from = [[Bophuthatswana Division]] |appealed to = |subsequent actions = |related actions = |opinions = |keywords = {{flatlist| *[[employment discrimination]] *[[equality before the law|equality]] *[[immigration|immigrants' rights]] }} }}{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Larbi-Odam v MEC for Education (North-West Province)''}} '''''Larbi-Odam v MEC for Education (North-West Province)''''' is a 1997 judgment of the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa]] which held that a government policy forbidding the employment of non-citizens (including permanent residents) in permanent teaching positions, was unconstitutional.<ref name="handbook">{{cite book |first1=Iain |last1=Currie |first2=Johan |last2=de Waal |title=The Bill of Rights Handbook |edition=5th |year=2005 |location=Cape Town |publisher=Juta & Company Ltd |isbn=9780702159237 |page=259}}</ref> Although citizenship is not one of the prohibited grounds for discrimination listed in the [[Section Nine of the Constitution of South Africa|equality clause]] of South Africa's [[Constitution of South Africa|Constitution]], the court found unanimously that in this case discrimination against non-citizens was unfair. It came to this decision because non-citizens are necessarily a minority with little political power, and because citizenship is a personal attribute which is difficult to change.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saflii.org/za/cases/ZACC/1997/16media.pdf |title=Media Summary: Larbi-Odam and Others v MEC for Education (North-West Province) and Another |publisher=Constitutional Court |date=26 November 1997 |accessdate=7 May 2013}}</ref>
